 Covid19 as an historical event, including their own experiences of living through history; their relationship with their surroundings, including their relationships with family, the soundscapes and the emotional environments of a pandemic world; the impact and tone of political rhetoric, including the use (and misuse) of wartime myths and language in the United Kingdom; and finally, what lessons can be learnt from how people discuss their own personal stories and what lessons can we draw from previous examples of storytelling in moments of crisis. The result is a fascinating and rich discussion derived from an archive full of idiosyncratic experiences of life changing during the Covid19 pandemic.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCorona. 4aCovid-19. 4aGeschichtsschreibung. 4aPandemie. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aCoronavirus.  aCovid-19.  ahistoriagraphy.  apandemic.1 aArwyn, Arddun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilippaki, Iro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoegaerts, Josephine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohlt, Franziska E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovell, Kristopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovell, Kristopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPalli, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Darren R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g